article.headline: Sting hits two field goals in final nine minutes
article.linkText: Fever ratchet up defense in victory over Sting
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Reserves Deanna Jackson scored 12 points and
Jurgita Streimikyte added 10 to lead the Indiana Fever to a 68-58
victory over the Charlotte Sting on Sunday.

Indiana limited Charlotte to just two field goals in the final 9
minutes to win its season opener.

Sheri Sam scored 13 points and Dawn Staley 10 for Charlotte
(0-2).

Three-time All-Star Tamika Catchings was in foul trouble
throughout and finished with nine points in 24 minutes for Indiana.
Natalie Williams added eight points and 10 rebounds for the Fever.

"Catch gave us a pep talk at halftime," Williams said of
Catchings. "She said, 'I'm in foul trouble. Everybody's got to
help out.' I think this year, our team is deeper. We have a lot of
people who can score and penetrate coming off the bench."

Indiana shot 36 percent (12-for-33) in the first half and
trailed 30-29, but limited Charlotte to 34 percent shooting
(9-of-26) in the second half.

"It's nice to win a game when Tamika Catchings struggles with
foul trouble," Fever coach Brian Winters said.

Winters praised his bench players, who scored 33 points.

"We have a lot of people who can play well with the minutes
they get," Winters said.

Tangela Smith's layup gave Charlotte a 48-46 lead with 9:11 to
play, but the Sting didn't hit another field goal until Sam sank a
3-pointer with 1:47 remaining.

By then, the Fever had taken a seven-point lead. Sam's shot cut
the deficit to 62-58, but Streimikyte and Kelly Miller had three
points each as the Fever scored the final six points of the game.

"We didn't play well," said Sting coach Trudi Lacey. "At the
end we needed to get some stops, needed to hit free throws."

Sting forward Janel McCarville strained her lower back with just
under 6 minutes left in the first half and didn't return.
